                            "isMainLine": false,
                            "annotation": {
                              "moveRationale": "White hops the knight into opponent's territory, which is not a good move, of course. It is easily kickable, which only helps black to develop pieces and makes position worse for white because they lose more and more tempo.",
                              "strategicTheme": "Piece development",
                              "source": "wikibooks"
                            }
                          }
                        ],
                        "isMainLine": false,
                        "annotation": {
                          "moveRationale": "Of course black pushes further, forcing white to lose tempo and move the knight. White has a few responses to this:\n\n# Nfd2 - 61%; winrate 48% (w) -  49% (b)\n# Ne5 - 16%; winrate 45% -  53% - Reversed Mokele Mbembe\n# Ng1 - 16%; winrate 49% -  48% - Reversed Brooklyn.",
                          "strategicTheme": "Tempo play",
                          "source": "wikibooks"
                        }
                      }
                    ],
                    "isMainLine": false,
                    "annotation": {
                      "moveRationale": "This move may seem like a good response, and also is similar to Alekhine defense but from white side. However black can just push the pawn further and force the knight to move (if you don't want to lose it of course).",
